Test, one, two, three.
It doesn't have a little.
OK. Do you mind if I pull up this chair?
No.
This is an interview with Dr. Wendy Stock by Christine Aschenbeck on December 1st, 1992 at Texas A&M University in the Psychology Building concerning the feminist movement today.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I'm asking you to donate this tape to me onto the Texas A&M Oral History Collection website.
in the university archives.
Is that all right with you?
Yeah, that's fine.
Well, first, could we collect some biographical data?
Tell me about your life.
Where did you grow up?
I was born in 1954 in San Francisco, and I grew up there until I was 18.
I went to public schools.
I went to UC Berkeley for four years as an undergraduate and received my bachelor's in psychology in 1972.
And then I went to State University of New York at Stony Brook, which is on Long Island, New York.
And I was there for seven years, from 1976 to 1983.
And after seven years, received my doctorate and had received my master's in 1980 there.
And my doctorate is in the area of clinical psychology.
In 1983, when I finished, I took a job in Florida, West Palm Beach, Florida, for one year as the director of a clinic for the treatment of sexual dysfunctions.
And terminated that job after a year due to...
disagreements with my bosses who seemed interested in making a lot of money on medical procedures for male impotence rather than treatment, psychological treatment.
I became a research scientist in fall 1984 at Texas A&M.
and was in that position for two years as project coordinator on a National Institute of Health research grant on differentiating psychogenic from organic causes of erectile dysfunction.
In 1986, I was hired as a visiting assistant professor.
In 1987, I was hired tenure track, and I have completed my five years of tenure track.
and have been denied tenure by the university this fall, 1992.
I can talk more about the political stuff if that's what you want, like growing up, or unless you want to have specific questions on that.
I guess you'd mentioned going to Berkeley, and that must have been in the early 70s?
Yeah, 72 to 76.
neat time to be going there, I guess there was lots of activism at that time?
A fair amount, although I was always annoyed because I had missed the free speech movement, which occurred in the mid-60s, 1966, 1967.
And as a kid, when I was 13 in 1967, which was the Summer of Love in the San Francisco Haight-Ashbury, and I was a little hippie-type kid.
I was a straight-A student, but I adopted the jeans and the beads and
so forth.

And I also had been reading the paper and became convinced that Vietnam was a mistake, that we shouldn't be fighting there, and became active in the anti-war movement when I attended my first peace march at age 13 in San Francisco.
So my activism really started then, rather than when I started as a freshman at Berkeley.
My mother forbade me to go to the peace march.
She was afraid I'd get my head bashed in and
I went anyway, and she said that she would punish me, and I said, okay, and she did.
She grounded me from doing my volunteer work at an animal museum, which really upset me, but I still felt I had done the right thing.
So that kind of shaped the way that I've handled things since, which is if basically something seems right to me, I generally will do it, even if someone is threatening me because
it seems to me an important choice to have, to be able to do things like that.
So my mother contributed to my activism without really intending to at all.
And my father did, just by being such an authoritarian kind of tyrant.
He had been brought up in Germany, and he had very traditional German notions about discipline.
He used to say, you'll do what I do and you'll think what I think as long as you're under this roof.
And, of course, that had the absolute opposite effect.
So early, early in my teens, I really...
felt that I had a right to think for myself and was not going to be the robot of my parents' making.
So after this first anti-war demonstration, I became active in the student anti-war movement.

And in junior high and high school, I participated in demonstrations, peaceful demonstrations, moratoriums where we had walkouts during school time to protest the war, pamphleting, writing letters, walking in peace marches.
I never have supported violence as a means for social change.
There may be conditions under which that would be necessary, but I haven't experienced those conditions myself.
And I pretty much abhor the use of violence on people, or anyone, and living creatures.
So I was active in that movement.
I got suspended once in high school for doing an anti-war activity.
And this was really difficult for my mother, who was a public school teacher, to handle, that I was getting in trouble for anything
and she didn't really care a lot.
I also became active in the United Farm Workers movement.
These were very underpaid Hispanic workers coming from Mexico generally and were paid less than the minimum wage and had been
subjected to pesticide use that caused them to have a lot of illness and cancer.

So they were striking, there was a grape strike and then a lettuce, grape boycott and lettuce boycott and I helped with other students, helped picket for the farm workers and it was sort of like a student group that would do this sort of activity.
And we tried to educate people about their situation and their need for a union, which the boycott was in support of Cesar Chavez's union.
And also I was a member of the Sierra Club and got very into the ecology movement in high school.
I was into recycling.
We recycled cans and glass and newspaper and all the stuff that people are doing still now.
And I thought I might go into that as a career, to go into something to do with ecology or conservation of natural resources.
I wasn't sure what I was going to do in high school.
I also became aware of feminism.
I read this book, Sisterhood is Powerful.
It's like an early feminist work, an anthology of writings.
And another one called Woman in Sexist Society.
And then I also had the first edition of Our Bodies, Our Cells, which now has like...
quadrupled in size, I think.
Who is that book by?
Boston Woman's Health Collective.
It was out in newsprint when I first got it.
Now it's this huge book and there's so much more information.
So I realized, well, I'm a woman and these things are going to apply to me and in some ways already do.
It seemed to me like another important struggle.
And so I just felt that a big part of my life was trying to change social conditions and trying to make the world better.
And I thought perhaps maybe I would someday join the Peace Corps or VISTA.
So in high school, those were my concerns.
I wasn't specifically interested in psychology.
There wasn't even a class in it, so I was interested in people.
I just didn't really know what direction I was going to take in college.
I started out in Berkeley as pre-med.
How did you choose Berkeley?
It was the closest major university in the area and I had pretty high scores and grades.
My mother went there and that
Really, that was the one thing that I agreed with her on.
I think she has very good taste in the university.
That I like the campus, and it was the highest quality university in my area.
And I thought it would be the place to go.
And the political activism there appealed to me, because we used to see what was going on there.
And then in our student groups, we would try to replicate some of those things.
And Berkeley was a very active place.
During the time I was there, the United States was still bombing in Vietnam and Cambodia.
And my freshman quarter in spring of 72, we had invaded, I believe, Cambodia.
And I think the Gulf of Tonkin was happening around then.
And there was a huge moratorium and strike by students at the university to shut down the university and protest.
And it was really, it may seem strange in retrospect, but it was the only way students felt they could be heard.
They weren't workers.
They couldn't strike their place of work.
People did write letters and petition.
But absenting themselves from the place where they were basically working as students was the only way they felt they could have an impact.
So I was involved in that strike.

And what happened is some of the people that were in the anti-war movement, mostly the street people who hung out around the university who were not students, became violent during these demonstrations and started throwing things into the windows of local merchants, which was really stupid because most of the merchants were supportive of the anti-war movement.

Anyway, they destroyed a lot of property about a block away from where I lived in the dorms, and I remember studying for midterms my first time ever in college, having to put wet towels under the cracks of the door and windows because tear gas was coming in, and I didn't want to inhale tear gas and be unable to study for my tests.
I had to go through two tax squads to get in and out of my dorm for several weeks during my first quarter.
So that made an impression on me.
I also saw the Oakland police drive like 60 miles an hour down a street that was filled with people just walking.
And if anyone had not been able to get out of the way, they would have been run over.
And I saw these guys with their billy clubs advancing on peaceful demonstrators and I know people who were beaten up.
that weren't throwing rocks and that were just, like, going to class.
So that also politicized me.
It made me even more distrustful of the police and the abuses that the police have been put to historically in this country.
You're probably aware how they could use to break up strikes and kill people, even, like, carrying silkwood on people's backs.
So I saw them doing this to people that weren't being violent and destructive, and I think it was educational, kind of chilling.
What was your first activity towards the feminist movement, or when did that become a main concern with you?
There wasn't really a feminist group in high school, and I wasn't a member of a feminist group in college.
I wasn't a member of NOW.
NOW seemed very, like, middle class and too traditional in Berkeley.
I worked as a rape counselor for a while, and that continued to make me more aware of women's issues.
There were women's studies classes, and I took a number of comparative lit courses in women and literature.
I took a year's worth to satisfy some of my requirements, and I became aware of women writers, and that a lot of them were writing feminist kinds of works, even earlier writers.
like Doris Lessing and Grace Paley and some of the new writers were coming out with fairly feminist material.
So it was actually through literature and in psychology there were studies that were starting to be done in the area of psychology of women and I just scarfed these things up.
I also lived in an all-women's

living situation called a student cooperative for four years and I guess through living in that situation I became aware of how much women could do because we did our own maintenance and so I became a part of the maintenance crew and learned how to do wiring and learned how to do the drill and electric saws and
Cousinly masculine.
Right.
And I'd never been particularly socialized to be traditionally feminine.
My mother was a whack in the army in World War II.
So she was really kind of a tomboy when she was growing up.
And she never enforced femininity on me.
But I hadn't had the experience of working in male kinds of trades and things.
And this taught me that I could do a lot more than I realized.
And other women were even better at it than I was.
And there were women who were electronics experts and wiring experts.
And I was like, I was educated by that.
And I also assumed leadership in the house.
I was the manager for a year.
That leadership experience was useful.

So it's sort of by immersion in a woman-run situation and working in the rape crisis center and reading psychology of women articles that were just beginning to come out at that time, looking at the issue of sex differences and finding there really aren't that many, realizing that a lot of this role had been hoisted on a woman by brainwashing, cultural brainwashing, and that it wasn't really inherent.

So I decided that women's issues would probably be my focus, and as I applied for graduate school in my senior year, what I hoped to do was to get into a program where I could do my master's thesis and doctoral work on psychology of women, and particularly what interested me was therapy for women, and what kinds of therapy would help women
to kind of throw off their social role and develop themselves more as full individuals.
So I had started to read some of the beginning work in feminist therapy.
Is that how you came to be interested in sexual therapy?
Well, kind of by mistake, actually.
When I got to graduate school, there was no one on the faculty who was doing psychology of women.
There was only one female faculty member out of 15, and she worked with autistic children.
And I don't like children.
I don't like to work with children.
That was the last thing in the world I wanted anything to do with.
And no one was doing feminist stuff.
I was interested in consciousness-raising groups, and did those have a therapeutic effect?
And I wanted to test that.
No one was doing that.
There was a woman in another department who was the head of women's studies, but she was already overcommitted, and she couldn't take me on.
And that felt like a crushing blow that
They just wasn't a mentor for me in my area.
So I asked around in the psych department and found that there was a researcher in the clinical area who did sex research and he wanted someone to do sex research on women.
And his student that he had been a mentor for had gone on and finished her doctorate and he had a

opening for another student so i talked with him and i decided to work with him since sexuality was always interesting to me and i felt that women were oppressed in many ways sexually and that we had a lot to learn about female sexuality and i thought i could integrate my interest in feminism and women psycho woman with sexuality so i would not have thought of that field right off the bat it
It had always been an interesting area to me, but I'd never thought of myself as going into sex research.
But once I got in, I realized that the potential for working as a feminist sex researcher was very high, that I could do a lot.
And plus, I then became fascinated by the field, that it's just, to me now, an inherently fascinating field.
Did today's research in sexual behavior, human sexual behavior, how has that field of study helped deteriorate the myths of
of the inequalities between men and women?
Well, some of the physiological research has shown that women can become sexually aroused as easily and as quickly as men.
That if you look at how long it takes for women to reach orgasm on their own, it's just as quick as men.
So this myth that women take longer, you know, and that they're less sexual has been disproven.
It's really whether they're getting adequate stimulation or not from their partners.
And unfortunately, a lot of
Men in our culture have not yet been educated enough to know how to be a lover, a good lover, to women.
And women themselves have not felt entitled to speak up about what they want.

Some of the other research has resulted in women becoming more aware of their bodies and how their bodies work and so that they're more able to communicate and less ashamed of their sexuality than women used to be.
But I think we have a long way to go.
So in dealing with sexual therapy, I would imagine that you would come across many studies dealing with relationships and the roles that men and women do play in them.
So I would imagine that, would that also be, contribute to deteriorating the socialization?

Yeah, in addition to the physiological end of the research, the research that we know we have known in relationships shows how important communication is and how important affectionate touching is to women, particularly.

and how important equality is in a relationship for marital and sexual happiness, that there is research showing that women are most highly sexually satisfied when they're in egalitarian relationships, plus they're more satisfied and happy in the relationship anyway.
And those things tend to go together for women, that it's very hard for women to be sexually happy if they are not emotionally happy in the relationship, because those things are very connected.
You were saying that you try to incorporate some of your feminist viewpoints into human sexual behaviors in psychology.
I was wondering how would you define feminism?
To me, it's the right to be treated equally to men and to have all the same advantages and privileges and opportunities.
in our culture and our society.
But men do.
Equal opportunity.
Yeah.
Okay.
There was a book, I don't know if you read it since you were talking about reading about early books published by women about studies dealing with women's roles.
It was called Betty Freedom, The Feminine Mystique.
In her book, she makes a comparison between a woman's role in the house.
She makes a comparison between the American household and a concentration camp.
It's pretty radical.
But I was wondering, how do you feel, how has that role changed?
Hmm.
For Dan's book, it actually came out when I was a little kid, I think in the early 60s, and I did read it later in my 20s as an historical work.
And I don't remember that comparison.
I think...
Some things have changed about that role, and some things have not.
A lot more women, half of all women now, I think, work outside the home.
Half of all mothers work outside the home.
And so women are not constrained as much to just having that one source of reinforcement, which isn't much of a source of reinforcement.
The problem with House being a homemaker traditionally has been that the work is invisible.
No one comes around and compliments you or acknowledges you.
It's unpaid.
No one gives you bonuses or pay raises.
It's isolated in that you're working alone.
You're not working with other people.
And it's repetitive because every time, every day, the dishes have to be done again and the laundry has to be done again.
So there isn't a sense of completion and having a product, a finished product at the end.
It's just repetitive work.
And recognition for their work.
etc.

The problem is that women end up usually then doing twice as much work and there's a book that's written by a sociologist named Arlen Hauschild called The Second Shift and it talks about how women often work full-time jobs and then they come home and do 80% of the housework and child care if not more and get very little assistance.
So in some ways that hasn't changed because working two shifts is not exactly liberation.
How do you foresee that role changing in the future or do you
I hope it will change.
I feel like I have good predictive powers.
Women, I think, need to insist that men help them with their housework, and men need to be socialized to view this as part of their normal activities as well.
Parents bringing children up need to hopefully raise boys and girls to feel that they'll be equal partners and take equal responsibility for all things in a relationship.
And this is going to be a long-term change, I'm sure.
But I think that for the short term, women in relationships are just going to have to demand that this person that they're with help them, not do the work themselves.
On the issue of equality between women and women, it brings me to the subject of now.
The National Organization of Women.
And I was wondering how, I know you've done research on pornography.
Is this movement active on the pornography issue?
Actually, now it's split on that issue as are most other feminist organizations.

There is a platform in now, a position that pornography is oppressive to women, and where they're split is whether or not to support the legislation, the model anti-pornography ordinance proposed by Dworkin and McKinnon.
Another way that they're split is in terms of where now is placing its priorities.
I had a chance to talk with the president of now this last August, Joel Ireland, who came to

the Texas Now conference in Beaumont and had lunch, I got to have lunch with her and a group of activists from Texas and I asked her about the pornography issue specifically and what about Now's platform and what are they going to be doing and she said, well, you know, it's an important issue and I do think it's harmful but we've got a lot of other things cooking right now that I think are more important to women such as abortion rights and I totally agree with her.
I mean, that's been, pornography has been my area of research for a long time and it's an area I
care about and feel strongly about.

But in women's day-to-day existence, if we have to decide which battles we're going to fight politically, I'm supportive of now fighting to keep freedom of choice in that area first and deal with the pornography later.
I'll still continue to work in both areas.
How has NOW's platform influenced legislation on reproductive rights?
Or what are some of the... How did they move to... Did they move to make people publicly aware of the issue?
Yeah, in a number of ways.
NOW has educational presentations at the chapter level.
Chapters are what you have in each city or town.
The Texas A&M chapter is one of the local ways that
now does educational presentations.
We show films.
We have discussions.
We show films sometimes from both the anti-abortion and pro-abortion and have people discuss it.
It's pretty hot sometimes.
And in addition to education, now engages in petitions and letter writing and lobbying of state representatives and national senators and congresspeople.
on that issue.

They also have a legal defense and education fund, which helps provide legal and financial support to people who are involved in lawsuits, and I believe that now has supported several legal battles having to do with abortion rights.
So it's active on a lot of fronts, trying to keep the option open for women to choose, and this is really important to understand that people are
glorifying abortion in this movement at all or thinking about that's the best strategy
of controlling pregnancy, but that women should have the choice.
I was wondering if we could look at the feminist movements you point on reproductive rights and then get back to other issues that now holds.
Would that be all right?
Yeah.
Okay.
What are some, how does, there are two, first I would like to discuss the division in feminism that you were speaking of.
There's a movement of radical feminism and then there's moderate, I believe.
Is that correct?
Well, yeah, there are different parts of feminists in this movement.
Do they all hold the same viewpoint on reproductive rights?
No.
Yeah, they're not divided on most issues.
Generally, there would be complete agreement on keeping abortion legal.
What is the difference between individuals of the feminist movement today?

I don't know if it's really as divided as the media presents it, because in general, the feminist movement is larger, now has a larger membership, and it's working more effectively than it ever has before to keep freedom of choice for women and to argue for other

sexual harassment issues so it's not like a split ineffective movement and there actually were there was an editorial by sally quinn there's this writer for the washington post who said feminism is dead and we feminism isn't addressing the needs of the common women and women and that was like um responded to by joe ireland and people would know and basically say this is bull you know that feminism is going strong and you don't know what you're talking about ladies
And it's true, it really is a big, strong movement.
And there are a lot of internal splits.
Historically, one split that was between maybe radical feminists and moderate feminists was over whether lesbians should be allowed to be members of NOW.
And this occurred in the late 60s.
Betty Friedan was against having lesbians be up front members of NOW and having a pro-lesbian or gay rights platform in NOW.
She felt that that would give
people more of a view that all feminists are lesbians, and that we couldn't afford as feminists to affiliate ourselves in this way, because that would lead to too much negative stereotyping.

And what happened is, actually, there were many women in now, not the majority, but maybe a third or a fourth of the women who started now who were lesbians, and they felt enraged by this, and really hurt, like they had gotten the whole thing going, and supported Friedan, and done a lot of the work, and been out there on the front lines, and
organized women's shelters and women's bookstores and now chapters.
And then they were being told that they were not wanted in the organization.
So they rose up and they formed this group called the Lavender Menace.
They took over the stage at one of these conventions and they demanded that Nell's policy change.
What happened is Nell did reject the lesbian members for several years and then its policy was changed and lesbians rejoin now.

So predominantly the membership is, you know, pretty heterosexual, but there's probably maybe less than a fourth, maybe a tenth of the membership, or some portion, maybe no more than the population proportion, maybe a tenth to a fifth are lesbians, because lesbians tend to have a feminist awareness because they're already oppressed in terms of their sexual orientation.
They also tend to share
the value of feminism, it'd be kind of nuts not to.
Right.
For them not to.
So that was one division, but that's kind of like now, you know, we have an openly bisexual president of now, Joe Ireland.
has come out, she was brought out, but she has publicly come out as having a female lover and still being married to her husband, who she loves very much and has been very supportive.
So, you know, best of both worlds, I guess.
I don't know how she does it, but she's been accepted, and people knew this about her and voted her in anyway.

So that division is by the wayside, and the only other division I can think of is the one over pornography, and that's not so much between moderate and radical feminists, because even among radical feminists,
There's division.

Some of them are saying women should have all kinds of pornography available to them, and that we are trying to protect women from sexuality in a way that's actually demeaning, that women are old enough, they're mature enough to make their own decisions, and blah, blah, blah.
And we don't want the government to censor more materials.
And then the other group is the Dworkin McKinnon group.
But that's really a split throughout.
all feminists about what to do with pornography.
So I wouldn't characterize there really being a radical feminist versus moderate feminist split.
Do you feel that the feminist viewpoint on pornography will be given legislative attention as has been done in Canada now?
Eventually, I think it will.
I've been asked to present at a conference coming up in March at the University of Chicago Law School, and thanks.
Dworkin's going to be there, McKinnon's going to be there, and these are people I know and I've met, but it's just going to be by kind of a think tank.
All of the activists who've worked in this area and scientists and researchers are going to be there and trying to talk about, all right, what strategy to take next.
And Anita Hill is going to be there.
She's going to be one of those speakers.
That's going to be interesting.
Oh, it's just going to be a dynamite conference.
So I think after that conference, people are going to sort of figure out where to go next with this.
But definitely the Canadian precedent is something that people are going to take and try to encourage to happen in the United States.
I'd say it probably will take at least another 10 years, at least.
It's a very hard fight because there's so many economic interests.

And I mentioned in class that the American Booksellers Association, which is Hastings and Wallen Books and all these huge corporations who profit from selling magazines, pornography magazines, don't want any control on that stuff because they'll lose millions of dollars in profits.
So they're funding the battle against.
It's not just pornographers.
It's like anybody else who benefits from it.
I was going to ask you about NOW and the correlation between NOW and the feminist movement.
Is NOW the only tool that the feminist movement has?
No, it's the largest national organization, but there's another one that Ellie Smeal started.
She was a former president of NOW, two presidents ago.
She started an organization called Feminist Majority, which funds candidates for office.
women candidates and actually helped fund a lot of the women who ran for senator and representative this time around.
And she believes, Ellie believes that
The only way women are going to really be able to change the system is to get elected to office.
We've got to put priority on that.
So there's that organization.
Many people are members of both.
I think I'm a member of both.
I know I'm a member of now, and I think I've paid my dues to the other one this year.
There's also specific abortion rights groups like National Abortion Rights Action League, NERA.
that's focused on just, you know, keeping abortion legal, and there are state divisions of that.
There's Terol, which is a Texas abortion rights action league.
Other feminist groups...
There's another one that's just started called the Third Party or something, and it's like to get a third political party that would be more responsive to the needs of women in minority groups.
I think that's another separate feminist organization.
But now it's really the biggest.
Okay.
Um...
What got you interested in teaching sexual behaviors?
Just in, I guess it wasn't an interest, it was my role when I applied to be a tenure track professor.

I'd already, I'd been allowed to teach some courses as an assistant professor who was visiting, but I hadn't taught the sex course yet because the person I was working with, who was my senior, taught the sexuality course here.
And so I just, it was part of the role I was hired for to teach that particular course.
And I knew immediately that it would be a wonderful course to teach.

And the challenge for me was to teach it in a way that gave the students the basic information that's in the text, but also gave them more of a critical awareness that this isn't the only information, that there are different points of view, that this is still a social construct that we need to be aware of, the point of view of the researchers.
And it's hard to do that with an undergraduate class, because it would be easy to talk about people's heads.
But it seems to me the students really do get the idea after a while.
understand why some of the readings are there.
The only way to do that is to have this huge amount of reading, to have the textbook and to have these articles which give different points of view on the side.
Do you feel more in any way gratified that you're doing, that you are educating undergraduate students on this subject in what has been a traditional conservative school?
Yeah, I really do.

I didn't think about that when I started, but I really soon became aware that the person who teaches that sort of a course, probably anywhere, but especially maybe a place like Texas A&M, that they're addressing a need for information that has not been addressed for many of these students before, and that so many of the students in my classes come and talk to me after class, or they'll come in and shut the door, and they'll say, right,

this happened to me or I have a question and they've never been able to ask anybody before and I realize that there is an atmosphere of trust that happens in that class and that's very important and that I can help individual students as well as teaching these ideas and in terms of challenging traditional beliefs I do think that the class succeeds in doing that and that it opens people to a different point of view that I don't think that they would have gotten exposure to

I know if I was teaching this course in New York or California where I'm from, I would just sort of be like, oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, you know, we know that, and I would just sort of be like, you know, like a lot of other profs there, and the students would
They're not all completely educated and liberated, but they would have more of an idea.
And now here I feel almost like a missionary in a strange place.
I'm speaking these things like, oh, women have equal rights, and people are all freaked out.
And I'm saying, no, women are sexual too.
And I can see some of the guys shifting around going, women aren't sexual.
We're just supposed to lie there.
And I don't think anyone would say that, but...
I think that some people come in with those kinds of attitudes, and I can tell that people are thinking a lot about the course.
And I've had students come up to me later, like years later, and say, wow, that course was really a good course, and it really made me think, and it's really helped me in my relationships.
And that's important to me.
In a nutshell, what would you say your teaching strategy was for the class?
What is the class about?

The goal of the course, the objective, is to help students to have a critical understanding of sexuality, meaning an understanding of how sexuality is created in our society, where it comes from, where our ideas and beliefs come from, and a greater appreciation for the malleability of sexuality, that even if you're brought up
in a certain way, that there are many other people who believe very differently.

And maybe an understanding of cultural differences and an appreciation for people who are different sexually, like gay and lesbian individuals, an understanding of people who are gender dysphoric, rather than just a condemnation or prejudice, to understand what might make somebody feel this way.
So I guess creating greater awareness and understanding of sexuality for themselves and for their people.
You said you have your doctorate in clinical psychology.
Have you ever... Have you ever been a sexual therapist?
Yes.
Yeah, I do have a part-time private practice.
I see about eight clients a week.
Okay.
While you're teaching.
Yeah.
